---
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import JudgmentWorksheet from '../../components/course/JudgmentWorksheet.astro';
import { TOOLS } from '../../lib/tools';

const tool = TOOLS.find((t) => t.slug === 'judgment-worksheet')!;
---

<Prose
  title={tool.title}
  description={tool.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Tools', href: '/tools/' }, { name: tool.title }]}
  kicker="Practice Tools"
>
  <p>
    Judging a chart is a procedure before it is an art: the question and its house, the Witnesses
    and Judge, the significators and their springings, the scan for perfection, the audit of
    aspects and company, and the weighing that becomes a sentence. This worksheet walks that
    canonical order one step at a time and assembles your notes into a draft judgment, the same
    instrument the course unlocks across
    <a href="/course/perfection-of-the-figure/">Lesson 7</a> and completes in
    <a href="/course/the-full-judgment/">Lesson 10</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Without JavaScript every step renders at once, which makes the page a printable worksheet.
    Paper is how it should be used in any case: the course's standing practice is the written
    judgment, filed in a journal where the verdict can one day face its outcome. The method
    itself is set out at <a href="/techniques/judging-the-figure/">Judging the Figure</a> and
    <a href="/techniques/modes-of-perfection/">The Modes of Perfection</a>; for practice
    material, <a href="/course/charts/">the course charts</a> carry eleven canonical casts with
    standing questions.
  </p>

  <JudgmentWorksheet />
</Prose>
